authors: Tero Karras, Miika Aittala, Samuli Laine, Erik H√§rk√∂nen, Janne Hellsten, Jaakko Lehtinen, Timo Aila
citations_APA: Karras, T., Aittala, M., Laine, S., H√§rk√∂nen, E., Hellsten, J., Lehtinen, J., & Aila, T. (2021). Alias-free generative adversarial networks. Advances in neural information processing systems, 34, 852-863.
relatedPapers_1: Ruiz, N., Li, Y., Jampani, V., Pritch, Y., Rubinstein, M., & Aberman, K. (2023). Dreambooth: Fine tuning text-to-image diffusion models for subject-driven generation. In Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF conference on computer vision and pattern recognition (pp. 22500-22510).
relatedPapers_2: Karras, T., Aittala, M., Aila, T., & Laine, S. (2022). Elucidating the design space of diffusion-based generative models. Advances in neural information processing systems, 35, 26565-26577.
explanation: Alias-Free Generative Adversarial Networks (StyleGAN3) eliminate spatial aliasing in image generation by enforcing continuous translation and rotation equivariance, producing more natural transformations and avoiding "texture sticking" issues present in previous GAN architectures.
highlights-1: Equivariant to translation and rotation even at sub-pixel scales.
highlights-2: Solves "texture sticking," creating smoother, more coherent image transformations.
highlights-3: Matches StyleGAN2 in FID while improving animation and video generation suitability.
limitations-1: Increased computational costs and training times.
limitations-2: Sensitive to aliasing in the training data.
limitations-3: Improvements only applied to the generator, not the discriminator.

name: DDPM
paperName: Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models
authors: Jonathan Ho, Ajay Jain, Pieter Abbeel
citations_APA: Ho, J., Jain, A., & Abbeel, P. (2020). Denoising diffusion probabilistic models. Advances in neural information processing systems, 33, 6840-6851.
relatedPapers_1: Ruiz, N., Li, Y., Jampani, V., Pritch, Y., Rubinstein, M., & Aberman, K. (2023). Dreambooth: Fine tuning text-to-image diffusion models for subject-driven generation. In Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF conference on computer vision and pattern recognition (pp. 22500-22510).
relatedPapers_2: Saharia, C., Chan, W., Saxena, S., Li, L., Whang, J., Denton, E. L., ... & Norouzi, M. (2022). Photorealistic text-to-image diffusion models with deep language understanding. Advances in neural information processing systems, 35, 36479-36494.
explanation: Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPMs) are generative models that create high-quality images by learning to reverse a noisy diffusion process. This approach combines score matching with Langevin dynamics, training a neural network to iteratively denoise data, yielding realistic samples.
highlights-1: High-quality samples: Achieves competitive Inception and FID scores on CIFAR-10 and LSUN datasets.
highlights-2: Connection to score matching: Links diffusion models with denoising score matching and Langevin dynamics.
highlights-3: Progressive generation: Supports lossy image decompression with fine-to-coarse details during sampling.
limitations-1: Lower likelihood performance: Does not achieve competitive log likelihoods with other likelihood-based models.
limitations-2: Training instability: Sensitive to parameter choices and variance schedule settings.
limitations-3: High computation cost: Requires extensive neural network evaluations, impacting sampling speed.

name: Improved DDPM
paperName: Improved Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models
authors: Alexander Quinn Nichol, Prafulla Dhariwal
citations_APA: Nichol, A. Q., & Dhariwal, P. (2021, July). Improved denoising diffusion probabilistic models. In International conference on machine learning (pp. 8162-8171). PMLR.

relatedPapers_2: Nichol, A., Dhariwal, P., Ramesh, A., Shyam, P., Mishkin, P., McGrew, B., ... & Chen, M. (2021). Glide: Towards photorealistic image generation and editing with text-guided diffusion models. arXiv preprint arXiv:2112.10741.
explanation: Improved Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (DDPMs) are generative models that reverse a multi-step noising process. This improved DDPM variant learns the reverse process more efficiently, achieving high-quality samples with faster sampling and competitive log-likelihoods, making it suitable for scalable, practical applications.
highlights-1: Achieves competitive log-likelihoods with high sample quality.
highlights-2: Allows fast sampling with fewer forward passes.
highlights-3: Improved mode coverage over GANs, enhancing distribution coverage.
limitations-1: Requires large compute resources for training.
limitations-2: Slower sampling compared to GANs.
limitations-3: High gradient noise during optimization affects training stability.

institution: Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich & IWR, Heidelberg University, Germany

explanation: Latent Diffusion Models (LDMs) generate high-resolution images by training diffusion models in a compressed latent space, significantly reducing computational resources without sacrificing quality. This allows for efficient and versatile applications, including super-resolution, inpainting, and text-to-image synthesis.
highlights-1: Reduced computational demands with latent-space training.
highlights-2: High-quality synthesis through minimal downsampling.
highlights-3: Supports diverse conditioning inputs like text and layout.
limitations-1: Requires a pretrained autoencoder.
limitations-2: Still computationally demanding for very high resolutions.
limitations-3: Limited generalization to unconventional conditioning setups.

name: Stable Diffusion XL
paperName: SDXL: Improving Latent Diffusion Models for High-Resolution Image Synthesis
authors: Dustin Podell, Zion English, Kyle Lacey, Andreas Blattmann, Tim Dockhorn, Jonas M√ºller, Joe Penna, Robin Rombach

explanation: SDXL is an improved text-to-image latent diffusion model using a larger UNet backbone, two text encoders, and novel conditioning techniques to generate high-quality, high-resolution images with better detail and composition.
highlights-1: Larger UNet model with 2.6B parameters enhances image synthesis quality.
highlights-2: Dual text encoders improve prompt understanding and adherence.
highlights-3: Refinement model enhances image detail and fidelity post-generation.
limitations-1: High VRAM and compute requirements for two-stage generation.
limitations-2: Struggles with rendering fine details, like hands and intricate text.
limitations-3: May exhibit concept blending in complex scenes.

name: SDXL Turbo

explanation: Adversarial Diffusion Distillation (ADD) reduces high-fidelity image diffusion model sampling steps to just 1‚Äì4 steps by combining adversarial and distillation losses, enabling real-time, high-quality generation.
highlights-1: Achieves single-step, high-quality image generation.
highlights-2: Outperforms comparable few-step models in image fidelity.
highlights-3: Retains quality across iterative sampling steps.

limitations-2: Pretrained model initialization required.
limitations-3: Reduced effectiveness with certain teacher models (e.g., SDXL).

name: IP-Adapter
paperName: IP-Adapter: Text Compatible Image Prompt Adapter for Text-to-Image Diffusion Models
authors: Hu Ye, Jun Zhang, Sibo Liu, Xiao Han, Wei Yang
citations_APA: Ye, H., Zhang, J., Liu, S., Han, X., & Yang, W. (2023). Ip-adapter: Text compatible image prompt adapter for text-to-image diffusion models. arXiv preprint arXiv:2308.06721.

explanation: The IP-Adapter enables image prompts in text-to-image diffusion models by adding separate cross-attention layers for text and image features. It maintains high generation quality with minimal parameters, allowing multimodal image generation using both text and image prompts without modifying the original model.
highlights-1: Lightweight design with only 22M parameters, comparable to fully fine-tuned models.
highlights-2: Compatible with text prompts, enabling multimodal generation.
highlights-3: Works with existing structural control tools like ControlNet.
limitations-1: Limited ability to capture highly specific subject features.
limitations-2: Only approximate faithfulness to reference images.
limitations-3: Multimodal generation lacks full customization consistency.

name: Sora

highlights-2: Adapts to diverse resolutions and aspect ratios.
highlights-3: Maintains long-range consistency in object and environment rendering.
limitations-1: Struggles with complex physical interactions like glass shattering.

limitations-3: Occasional unintended object appearances.

explanation: Lumiere is a text-to-video diffusion model that uses a Space-Time U-Net architecture to generate coherent, realistic motion in videos. Unlike traditional models, it processes an entire video sequence at once, ensuring temporal consistency without relying on cascaded temporal super-resolution.
highlights-1: Generates coherent motion by processing entire video duration at once.
highlights-2: Facilitates varied applications: image-to-video, inpainting, stylized generation.
highlights-3: Uses efficient space-time downsampling to reduce computational demands.
limitations-1: Limited to single-shot, continuous scene videos.
limitations-2: Challenges with high-resolution generation due to memory constraints.
limitations-3: Not optimized for scene transitions or multi-shot videos.

highlights-3: Supports complex, varied mesh topologies and lighting effects.

limitations-2: Currently trained per-category, limiting multi-category application.
limitations-3: Evaluated on synthetic data only, not real-world data.
